Cisco Nexus 9000 Series Switches Portfolio

The Cisco Nexus 9000 Series is the next generation of data center switching infrastructure and is suitable for applications requiring high performance, scalability, and programmability. Both standalone Cisco Nexus Operating System (NX-OS) mode and Cisco Application Centric Infrastructure (ACI) fabric mode are supported. The Cisco Nexus 9000 Series offers a powerful combination of hardware and software to provide latency, congestion management mechanisms, and telemetry to meet the requirements of AI/ML applications. The Cisco Nexus 9200 and 9800 Series use Cisco Silicon One ASIC chips, whereas the Cisco Nexus 9300, 9400, and 9500 Series use Cisco Cloud Scale ASIC chips.

The key features of Cisco Nexus 9000 Series Switches include the following:

  • High performance: This feature supports 1-, 10-, 25-, 40-, 50-, 100-, and 400-Gbps interfaces for high throughput and low latency.

  • Scalability: This feature is ideal for both traditional and cloud environments with flexible architectures.

  • Advanced management: This feature streamlines provisioning and obtains actionable insights with the Cisco Nexus Dashboard.

  • Programmability: This feature supports Cisco NX-OS and Cisco ACI for automated and policy-driven network management.

  • Security: This feature integrates security features such as microsegmentation and threat defense.

  • Advanced telemetry: This feature provides real-time network visibility with enhanced telemetry and analytics.

The Cisco Nexus 9000 Series family supports both fixed and modular switches. Cisco Nexus 9000 fixed switches include the following:

  • Cisco Nexus 9200 Series Switches

    1. Features: Cost-effective fixed switches; 1-, 10-, 25-, 40-, and 100-Gbps interfaces

    2. Use case: Data center top-of-rack deployments

  • Cisco Nexus 9300-EX and FX Series Switches

    1. Features: High-density fixed switches; 1-, 10-, 25-, 40-, 50-, and 100-Gbps interfaces

    2. Use case: Top-of-rack and spine deployments in data centers

  • Cisco Nexus 9300-GX Series Switches

    1. Features: High-performance fixed switches; 400-Gbps interfaces

    2. Use case: High-bandwidth applications, data center spine-leaf architecture

Note

Cisco Nexus 9200 Series Switches and Cisco X9600 and X9400 Series line cards are not designed for Cisco ACI.

The Cisco Nexus 9000 Series modular switch family has been expanded and includes the following members.

Explore Cisco Nexus 9000 Series Modular Switches Family Members

Click the switch families or press the numbers 1 through 3 on your keyboard to learn more about each switch family.

Note

The entire Cisco Nexus 9000 Series family is designed to support AI/ML workloads. This training focuses on Cisco Nexus switches chosen in the Cisco Data Center Networking Blueprint for AI/ML Applications white paper: Cisco Nexus 9332D-GX2B as a spine switch and Cisco Nexus 93600CD-GX as a leaf switch.

Shared 100 Gbps AI/ML-Ready Network Use Case

How a network is designed has a large impact on the overall performance of the AI/ML cluster. The network should provide a nonblocking fabric to accommodate all the traffic generated by the GPUs. This approach reduces the need for congestion management algorithms and allows faster completion of AI/ML jobs.

Note

There are several ways to build a nonblocking network, but a two-tier, spine-switch-leaf-switch design provides scalability and the lowest latency. To illustrate this design, you will use an example of a company that wants to create a GPU cluster with 1024 GPUs, and storage devices to store data that the GPUs need to process.

In the following example, there are eight GPUs per server, and each server is dual-homed to two separate leaf switches for network redundancy. To accommodate 128 servers with two 100-Gbps ports, 256 ports with 100-Gbps speed are required at the access layer. To handle the amount of traffic coming from the leaf switches, eighty 400-Gbps ports are needed. For redundancy reasons, two spine switches can be installed, but because scale and resiliency are crucial for AI/ML workloads, the system will be built with four spine switches. In the example shown here, low latency is important, so a spine-leaf switch network with Cisco Nexus 9300 Series Switches is recommended.

To make it a nonblocking network, the uplinks from the spine switches must have the same bandwidth capacity as the server-facing ports.

To meet the requirements of the leaf (access) layer, the Cisco Nexus 93600CD-GX switch is used. The Cisco Nexus 93600CD-GX switch has twenty-eight 100-Gbps ports that can be used as server ports and eight 400-Gbps uplinks. This collection of downlink and uplink ports creates this a nonblocking switch.

This design ensures that ports are available to connect to storage devices or storage clusters and to connect this AI/ML server cluster to other parts of the enterprise network.

The Cisco Nexus 9332D-GX2B switch is used as the spine switch. The spine switches will each connect 20 400-Gbps ports. Therefore, 12 ports remain free on each spine switch, so additional leaf switches can be added to expand this environment without risking the nonblocking aspect of the network.

Note

For building very large-scale and high-throughput AI/ML fabrics, you could use Cisco Nexus 9800 Series spine switches. Cisco Nexus 9800 Series Switches use 400-Gbps and 100-Gbps line cards, which are based on Cisco Silicon One Q200 ASICs.

You have built a nonblocking network; however, congestion management algorithms should still be used to accommodate the best performance and ensure a lossless Ethernet fabric. Even in a nonblocking network, congestion is possible, such as when two servers send at a line rate to a single server. As already mentioned, ECN and PFC should be used.

The latency of the Cisco Nexus 93600CD-GX leaf switches and the Cisco Nexus 9332D-GX2B spine switches is 1.5 microseconds. The maximum end-to-end latency for this network fabric is approximately 4.5 microseconds for traffic that must traverse leaf and spine switches to reach its destination. With congestion, which is usually managed by Weighted Random Early Detection (WRED) ECN, the latency that is provided by the RoCEv2 transport on the endpoints can be preserved.

Note

To reduce latency, you can connect latency-sensitive machines to the same pair of leaf switches.

The preceding example network can easily be expanded as follows:

  • Add more leaf switches.

  • Double the spine capacity using Cisco Nexus 9364D-GX2A spine switches, which have sixty-four 400-Gbps ports.

  • Add more spine switches to maintain a nonblocking fabric.

  • Use a three-tier (super spine type) design to interconnect multiple non-blocking network fabrics.
